LAGOS – The Managing Director and Chief Executive Officer of Nigeria LNG Limited (NLNG), Tony Attah, yesterday in Port Harcourt, said the company was 100% committed to a Train 7 project that will be delivered with the involvement of competent Nigerian companies. The project, valued at over $4 billion, is expected to commence as soon as a Final Investment Decision (FID) is taken. It is also expected to ramp up the company’s production capacity by 35% from 22 Million Tonnes Per Annum (MTPA) to 30 MTPA. He spoke at a workshop titled “Public Workshop on Nigerian Content for NLNG’s Train 7 Development” held at Hotel Presidential in Port Harcourt, targeted at giving Nigerian companies information on how Nigerian Content can be maximised in NLNG Train 7 project. In his welcome remarks, Tony Attah, said: “NLNG is underpinned by its vision of being ‘a global LNG company helping to build a better Nigeria’. The global play is about the business itself and helping to build a better Nigeria is consist with our partnership with NCDMB. “I will like to invite Nigerian companies to please participate in Train 7, which is the purpose of this workshop. It is consistent with our partnership with NCDMB. It also opens up the opportunities for local companies to play, starting with understanding the scope of the project. In addition, it creates an opportunity to meet the two consortia we are currently working with, B7 JV and SCD JV. They are the key players tasked with the Front End Engineering Design (FEED),” he added. Speaking, the Nigerian Content Development Monitoring Board Executive Secretary, Simbi Wabote, commended NLNG for the workshop, saying “we had one of it in Bonny community and another in Abuja. Today, we are here in Port Harcourt.